5000|$|The United States Federal Aviation Administration defines an ARTCC as: [...] a {{facility}} established to provide {{air traffic control}} service to aircraft operating on <b>IFR</b> <b>flight</b> plans within controlled airspace, principally during the en route phase of flight. When equipment capabilities and controller workload permit, certain advisory/assistance services may be provided to VFR aircraft.|$|R
5000|$|The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) Instrument Flying Handbook defines IFR as: [...] "Rules and {{regulations}} {{established by the}} FAA to govern flight under conditions in which flight by outside visual reference is not safe. <b>IFR</b> <b>flight</b> depends upon flying by reference to instruments in the flight deck, and navigation is accomplished by reference to electronic signals." [...] It is also a term used by pilots and controllers to indicate the type of flight plan an aircraft is flying, such as an <b>IFR</b> or VFR <b>flight</b> plan.|$|R
50|$|<b>IFR</b> <b>flights</b> in {{controlled}} airspace require an ATC clearance for {{each part of}} the flight. A clearance always specifies a clearance limit, which is the farthest the aircraft can fly without a new clearance. In addition, a clearance typically provides a heading or route to follow, altitude, and communication parameters, such as frequencies and transponder codes.|$|R
50|$|Managed by SATA Gestão de Aeródromos, {{it has an}} 1754 m {{operational}} runway (oriented 09/27), with a {{width of}} 45 m. The runway is illuminated and can handle evening flight operations (although rare), using VFR or <b>IFR</b> <b>flight</b> rules, while approximation instruments are based on PI locators. The installation of an ILS system was adjudicated around 2010.|$|R
5000|$|Charts {{used for}} <b>IFR</b> <b>flights</b> contain an {{abundance}} of information regarding locations of waypoints, known as [...] "fixes", which are defined by measurements from electronic beacons of various types, {{as well as the}} routes connecting these waypoints. Only limited topographic information is found on IFR charts, although the minimum safe altitudes available on the routes are shown.|$|R
